    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n                <jats:p>\n                  This paper presents mathematical modeling and quantitative evaluation of Large Scale Social Restriction (LSSR) in Jakarta between 10 April and 4 June 2020. The special capital region of Jakarta is the only province among 34 provinces in Indonesia with an average Testing Positivity Rate (TPR) below 5% recommended by the World Health Organization (WHO). The transmission model is based on a discrete-time compartmental epidemiological model incorporating suspected cases. The quantitative evaluation is measured based on the estimation of the time-varying effective reproduction number (\u211b\n                  <jats:sub>\n                    <jats:italic>t</jats:italic>\n                  </jats:sub>\n                  ). Our results show the LSSR has been successfully suppressed the spread of COVID-19 in Jakarta, which was indicated by \u211b\n                  <jats:sub>\n                    <jats:italic>t</jats:italic>\n                  </jats:sub>\n                  &lt; 1. However, once the LSSR was relaxed, the effective reproduction number increased significantly. The model is further used for short-term forecasting to mitigate the course of the pandemic.\n                </jats:p>",
